{"type":"message","id":"3dc7297b","parentId":"c54ff75c","timestamp":"2026-05-06T18:27:28.760Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking why Hermes (the agent framework running on their system) has the capability to help with coding tasks but doesn't proactively use those capabilities - they have to explicitly invoke it every time.\n\nThis is a design question about how Hermes/OpenClaw works. The key insight is:\n\n1. Hermes/OpenClaw is a reactive agent - it responds to messages but doesn't proactively scan or analyze your codebase unless specifically asked\n2. It doesn't have a codebase index or awareness of what you're working on\n3. It doesn't proactively read files or analyze code - it waits for you to give it a task\n\nThe user wants Hermes to be more proactive - like automatically understanding their codebase context, proactively offering help, etc.\n\nThe issue is that:\n- Hermes isn't watching your file system or code changes\n- It doesn't have persistent context about what project you're working on\n- It doesn't proactively search/analyze your codebase\n- It only responds when you explicitly ask it to do something\n\nSolutions could be:\n1. Use heartbeat to periodically check what you're working on and offer proactive help\n2. Use cron jobs to keep context fresh\n3. Set up better AGENTS.md/system prompt to encourage proactive behavior\n4. Use tools like Socraticode separately to analyze code and feed results to Hermes\n\nBut fundamentally, Hermes is designed as a reactive assistant, not a proactive coding partner that watches your work.\n\nLet me also check what capabilities Hermes actually has - maybe it has more code intelligence than the user realizes but isn't using it.","thinkingSignature":"6192a7645ca1786eed6af7d1d28e60d8969a8c0ee64ff9f41c39caaa2cc890af"},{"type":"text","text":"เพราะ Hermes เป็น **reactive agent** — มันรอคำสั่ง ไม่ได้คอยวิเคราะห์งานของคุณตลอดเวลา\n\n### ทำไม Hermes ไม่ค่อยออกฤทธิ์เอง:\n